column1: Will legislation eliminating the unit limit per manufacturer for the U.S. federal electric vehicle tax credit become law before 1 January 2020?
column6: ['Technology', 'US Policy']
column11: The Qualified Plug-In Electric Drive Motor Vehicle Credit applies to the first 200,000 units sold by a manufacturer (The IRS, Cornell Law). Tesla and GM each reached the unit limit in 2018 and are lobbying for the law to be changed (CNBC, Electrek). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

The IRS code was enacted in 2008 and stipulated the phased-out elimination of the tax credit based on manufacturer production. Since then states enacted additional incentives for the propping up of the electric vehicle market and jump start the alternative fuel vehicle economy. The side effect of this was lower revenue to the states via gasoline taxes which were not collected by an increasing all-electric vehicle fleet on the streets. Illinois and other states are considering huge increases in the annual registration fees for electric vehicles to augment the lost revenue from uncollected gasoline taxes. Trump has already announced he does not support extending the tax credits from the 2008 act beyond the existing parameters. Though legislation has been proposed to extend this tax incentive, it seems to be more of a election-cycle parlor game without much broad political appeal with legislatures and not much mainstream media attention. It appears this legislation has an uphill battle. On the other hand, pushing for tax incentives has broad public appeal and may be the political trick needed for many of the incumbent candidates need for their re-election cycle.

The crowd puts the chances at 10%. It does look like a longshot, especially given the current administration's hostility towards anything that reduces greenhouse gases. If the crowd is right, and I keep the chances at 3%, I'll get (0-0.03)^2 + (1-0.97)^2 + = 0.0018 Brier points. The average forecaster will get (1-0.9)^2 + (0-0.1)^2 = 0.02. I'll only beat the average by 0.0182 Brier points. So there isn't much downside for betting on the longshot having a slightly greater probability, but keeping the odds still fairly slim.

Lowering further. There are a number of possible scenarios where lawmakers extend credits somehow wihtout eliminating the unit limits. For example, lawmakers may simply increase the unit limits. After all, lawmakers do not want to commit to limitless subsidies. Such measures gain the support of detractors by including provisions that cap their overall costs. Unit limits are one way to do that (another might be to have a sunset clause in the form of: past year X, the credits are phased out gradually). Lawmakers may also sign a brand new law for incentivizing EVs.
Hard to say. I'm going to go with slightly less likely.

The tax credits date from the first two years of Obama's first term when Democrats controlled the Presidency, the House and the Senate. [1]. The tax credits are on the one hand popular with climate hawk democrats. At the same time, they draw ire from lawmakers who just see them as a way to allow rich people to buy cool cars. That's not a totally inaccurate view of the tax credits as their short term effect is indeed to make expensive cars slightly cheaper for those who can afford to buy a 50k+ car. Their long term effect is in fact to bring EV technology down its learning curve and usher an era of affordable EVs. But lawmakers may ignore long-term considerations in favor of more pressing issues for their constituents.
